{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_hodag_ver01/data/sn86086586/00414214496/1908022801/0616.xml":{"full_text":"Tuesday, March 3\nIS BARGAIN DAY!\nqpHESE SAIF'S are always widely patronized and should be more\nso this month than ever, for this reason that COTTON GOODS have reached\na lower level in prices, which will be demonstrated at this sale.\nLonnsdale Bleached Muslin at 10 cents per yard\nPepperell R Muslin at 8 cents per yard\nLonnsdale Cambric at 12*6 cents per yard\n42 inch Pillow Tubing at T 7 cents per yard\n45 inch Pillow Tubing at 18 cents per yard\n9-4 Bleached Sheeting at 25 cents per yard\nGinghams at 8 cents to 14 cents per yard\nPercales at 10c per yd. Prints at 6 cts. per yard\nSpecial Purchase for Bargain Day of\n500 yds. India Linen\n5c per yd. up to 30c.\nWe emphasize this as particulary STRONG\nATTRACTION.\nSpecial Attraction for Bargain Day\nDotted Swiss at 18c\nper yard* Good as you have bought for\n25 cents. A limited amount*\nLaces! Laces!\nAnew assortment not shown before*\nGood values at\n9 cents per jtard.\nGROCERY ATTRACTIONS\n20 pounds of pure Cane Sugar for SI.OO\n1 lb. package best Seeded Raisins for 10 cents\nBest Evaporated Peaches for 15 cents\nPuritan Flour for $1.35 per sack\n\nA special brand of Coffee bought green and roasted fresh every week. If you have\nnot tried it, buy a pound, at 15 cents per pound\nT\\ Edgerton,\nr\\ Ml HiIVK. I 9 Wisconsin.\nCORRESPONDENCE\nSumner\nW S Brill of Edgerton was in this\nviciuity last Monday.\nPrank Heble and family of Albion vis\nited Sunday with Mr and Mrs August\nLoga, Jr.\nWill Whittet of Milton Junction vis\nited with relatives at this place a few\ndays last week.\nMr and Mrs C Christenson visited\ntheir son Ludviek and family at Cam\nbridge last Saturday.\nMr and Mrs Adolph Kalment and sou i\nof Fort Atkinson visited relatives at this\nplace last week Sunday.\nMr and Mrs Willis Krokenberg\u2019s little\nbaby boy was taken sick Monday. Dr\nKeenan of Edgerton was called.\nA number from here attended the\nauction sale of Geo Dickinson on Albion\nPrairie last Monday afternoon.\nJohn Emrick, wife and two daughters,\nof Clear Lake, lowa, who have been vie\niting friends and relatives here for the\nppst month, will return home the first of\nthe week.\nThere is a camp of Indians about one\nmite north of this place, seven in num\nber, namely, Mr and Mrs War Club,\nMiss Mary Long Marsh, Messrs Thomas\nHopmkoh, Clay Long Marsh and Albert\nThunder, aod one little girl, Hunpke,\nthey being all related and belong to the\nWinnebago tribe. They are from the\nnorthern part of the state. Mr and Mrs\nWar Club and two girls have been here\nsince last October. Their wigwam is\nbeing kept warm and* comfortable as it\nis covered with heavy canvas and tar\npaper, heated by stove and is perfectly\nfree from smoke, which an ordinary In\ndian camp fire would cause. They make\ntheir living by means of trapping, mak\ning baskets, bows and arrows, bead work\nand tanniDg hides. They too feel the\nweight of the financial panic which is\nprevailing throughout the United States.\nThe head of the family, Mr War Club,\nhas been seriously ill with pneumonia,\nbut is gaining rapidly.\nPERRYS PERRY >oo< PERRY\nSPECIAL VALUES IN\nChildren\u2019s Hosiery\n3 PAIR FOR 25 CTS.\nSizes 5 l 2 to 9. Bought expressly for this\nday* A slight imperfection compels the\nreduction in price*\nMuslin Baby Bonnets\nLow price of 19 cents\nDaintily trimmed* Valued from 25 to 50\n.ents regular price*\nLadies\u2019 Neckwear.\nN\nA special lot valued at not less than 50\ncents up to 75 cents, at\n23 cts. while they last.\nAlbion Prairie\nJohn Bussey of Kansas is visitiDg rel\natives here.\nMrs Wilmer Slagg and children are\nvisiting friends at Green Bay.\nMr and Mrs Geo Hall entertained a\nnumber of young people Saturday eve.\nMonday evening a number of young\npeople surprised Miss Mildred Marsden.\nMrs Martha Haylock was the guest of\nMrs S Hall from Friday until Monday.\nLadies Aid Society of the P M church\nwill meet with Mrs George Silverwood\nnext week.\nMiss Mae Marsden had a quotation\nmatch at the school house Feb 14, Dan\niel Pierce receiving the honor of the con\ntest. All were masked until luncheon\nwas served. Avery profitable and en\njoyable evening was spent.\nCaledonia.\nMr and Mrs El L Earle visited Janes\nville friends one day last week.\nt The sick are all improving around\nhere. Some are yet troubled with the\nwhooping cough.\nMrs D E McCarthy attended the fun\neral of Miss Alice Moore at Edgerton\nlast week.\nMiss Abbie McCarthy spent Monday\nand Tuesday with her sisters-, Mrs*D E\nMcCarthy and Mrs\u00df L Earle.\nMiss Ethel McCarthy, who is attend\ning school at Evansville, spent a few\ndays at her home here.\nMiss Harriet Bennett of Madison uni\nversity and Miss Jennie Frusher spent\nlast Sunday with Mrs D E McCarthy.\nMrs D E McCarthy gave another of\nthose delightful card parties Monday\nDennis McCarthy, who played\nas a lady, got first prize. F Stems won\nthe gentleman\u2019s prize and C F McCarthy\nthe consolation.\nMrs Jim Earle gave a very pleasant\neard party to about forty of her friends\nlast Thursday evening. Progressive\ncinch was played until midnight when a\ndelicious lunch was served, after which\ndanciDg was indulged in till morning\nI dawned. Dennis McOarthy took the\ngentleman\u2019s prize, Mrs Mary Young the\nlady\u2019s and Dennie McCarthy the com\neolation. All wish that Mrs Earle will\nj soon entertain again.\nNINE CENT SALE\nFriday, Saturday, Monday, Feb. 28,29, March 2.\nSpecial 100 Piece\nDinner Set\n$7.50.\nA Regular \u00a7IO.OO value.\nChildren\u2019s 50c Blackboards\nat 39 cents.\nGlassware.\nOlive Dishes 9c\nSugar Bowls 9c\nButter Dishes 9c\nVases., 9c\nMany Other Articles, Including all 10 cent\nHANDTKE McREYNOLDS.\nMr and Mrs Will Porter met with a\nsad bereavement la9t Friday in the death\nof their youngest son. Paul, who died at\nthe Madison hospital after an operation\nfor appendicitis. Paul was a\\jtudent at\nthe university and was loved by all bis\nclass who attended his funeral at Cooks\nville, in a body. It is strange\nthat a young man like Paul should be\ntaken at the beautiful age of nineteen,\nwith such a bright future, but God\u2019s\nwill be done. The family have the heart\nfelt sympathy of all in their sad bereave\nment.\nIMPORTED\nF rer\\ch\nGinghams\n19 cts. per yd.\nRegular 25 cent goods.\nBought expressly for this sale\nSpecial Sale Silk Waistings\nJobbers' prices, 55 cts* Come in three\ndistinct patterns* The new radium effects*\nThis should induce customers to buy who\nwant somethingtasty for a small price*\nWhile they last, 45c yd.\nA Remarkable Sale of\nCorset Cover Embr\u2019ery\n150 yds. at 17c per yd.\nBest values in this line we have ever shown\nPillow Covers.\nI\nAnew lot bought expressly for this sale.\nRegular 50 cent values, at\nr 23 cents.\nStamped Table Covers\nANOTHER ATTRACTION\nX lot at 17e Regular value 25 cts\nI lot at 23c Regular value 50 cts\nRegular 10 Discount\non the rest of the entire stock, which has\nbeen replenished in all lines.\nLeather Goods at 9\u2019 cents.\nNOTIONS\nSide Combs 9c\nBack Combs 9c\nHair Brushes 9c\nClothes Brushes 9c\nTooth Brushes 9c-\nHair Curlers 9c\nTablets 9c\nBeads 9c\nGranite and Tinware\nBasins 9c\nPie Plates 9c\nSoap Dishes 9c\nCups 9c\nKettles 9c\nTea and Coffee Pots 9c\n\u2014Bardeen will be at studio Thursdays\nin future.\n\u2014Handtke Mc\u00dfeynolds, on Friday,\nSaturday and Monday Feb. 28 and 29,\nMarch 2, unique 9 cent sale.\n\u2014Miss Ena Berkev, piano instructor,\nwill receive pupils at the home of Mrs.\nGeo. Dotv every Friday and Saturday.\n41tf\n\u2014New spring suits, new waists. \u2014Ar-\nchie Reid A Cos., Janesville. 13w2\n\u2014The new spring photographs are on\nexhibition at Bardeen\u2019s.\nBABCOCK\u2019S\nCLOTHING STORE\nSpecial Bargain In\n48 pairs of Men\u2019s Kangaroo\nGrain Work Shoes just receiv\ned, $2.50 values, at\n$2.00 pair.\nthe lot consists of\n24 pairs of Men's Cap Toe. lace.